description.text:
Objects created from the remix project 'We Met Heads On' https://vimeo.com/43848831 Made with Processing. The video titled 'We Met Heads On' is my remix of the 3D scan hackathon at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in NY organised by Makerbot. The public were invited to scan artifacts to then modify and 3d print derivatives. I found 'decimation study - met heads' by scotta3d which is a derivative from another thingiverse user tbuser, and to continue the lineage of derivatives, I have placed the low-polygon heads from scotta3d into a Processing sketch that distorts the meshes in realtime in response to sound and outputs the modified stl objects. The soundwave is analysed from the streaming audio and used to force the mesh to twist to the strength of the soundwave. Performed and recorded in real-time. http://www.plummerfernandez.com/
https://twitter.com/M_PF

There are currently 2 heads, (1.1) more glitchy than the other (1.2) (The glitchy one may be difficult to print) 
You may want to carve out for yourself a booleaned cylinder before printing as this is a solid object. I decided to leave that step out so that you can make a derivative that suits your prefered wall thickness and overall size. I don't have a printer myself, so I'd be really grateful if you could print a copy and send me a photo of it! I'd credit you on my website for producing the first protoypes.
I really enjoyed making these objects, finding which of your favourite songs makes good mesh distortions and pressing 'save' everytime it does something cool is way better than using rhino! I'll try to get some more derivatives uploaded.

title: Interruptor Anet A8 // Switch Anet A8

description.text:
10-03-2018 v.2 Subida! / v.2 Uploaded! (v2 Horizontal.stl & v2 Vertical.stl)

Aún no la he probado, en unos días lo probaré y subiré fotos / Not tested yet, in a few days I will test it and upload photos.

  • MEJORAS / IMPROVEMENTS:

• Ahora queda cerrada por todos lados / Now is closed in all sides. (Imagen 3)
• Opción a poner el interruptor en vertical / Option to put the switch in vertical.
• Ahora es más alto, por lo que no quedaran ranuras entre la fuente y la pieza / Now is taller, so now aren´t going to be any "hole" between the power supply and the piece.
• He añadido un hueco más para un interruptor más / I added a new hole for an extra switch.
• He añadido una ranura para los cables del ventilador de la fuente de alimentación. / Added a slot for the cables of the power supply fan.
• Extensión de los agujeros para tornillos, para ajustarlo en altura. / Added a larger hole for the screw, to adjust the height of the piece.

Espero que te guste! Si deseas alguna modificación de esta pieza, habla conmigo! Gracias!
I hope you like it! If you wish any modification of this piece, tell me! Thank you!

--- ESPAÑOL ---

Encaja perfectamente con la fuente de alimentación original.

He creado esta pieza para poder ponerle un interruptor para apagar y encender la impresora facilmente. He puesto dos interruptores más, uno para los LEDS del extrusor, para ver bien la impresión, y otro para los ventiladores de la fuente de alimentación y la placa base. El principal propósito de esta pieza era poder desenchufar la impresora fácilmente sin que tener que quitar los cables, etc...

--- ENGLISH --- (Google Traductor)

it fits with the stock power supply

I created this piece so I could put a switch to turn the printer on and off easily. I have put two more switches, one for the extruder LEDS, to see the print well, and another one for the power supply and motherboard fans. The main purpose of this piece was to be able to easily unplug the printer without having to remove the cables, etc ...

Como montarlo / How to assembly it:

-ESPAÑOL:

Tiene dos agujeros a la derecha, para sujetarlo con dos tornillos a la fuente de alimentación. A la izquierda tiene un agujero alargado para sujetarlo con bridas a los agujeros de la fuente de alimentación. A las patas que tiene esta pieza le he puesto un poco de pegamento con la pistola de pegamento caliente para que no se mueva al encender los interruptores.

-ENGLISH:

It has two holes at the right to mount to the power supply with two screws.
At the left have one large hole to mount it with two zip ties to the holes in the power supply. To the legs that has this piece I have put some glue with the hot glue gun so that it doesn´t move when the switches are turned on/off.

LINKS:

-Interruptor IEC320 / IEC320 Switch: https://www.amazon.es/gp/product/B01F366T14/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

  • Fusible / Fuse (necesario para que funcione el Interruptor IEC320 / Necessary to get working the IEC320 Switch): https://www.amazon.es/gp/product/B01G6P1PJ2/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

  • Cable (Puede ser cualquier cable IEC320 / It could be any IEC320 Cable): https://www.amazon.es/gp/product/B01NH548Q4/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

  • Interruptor LED y ventilador / Switch LED and fans (Opcional / Optional) : http://www.gearbest.com/diy-parts-components/pp_237508.html?wid=21

description.text:
I needed a canopy that gave me enough space above the fuselage for stuff. My camera stuff is mounted in and on the nose so I dont need this place for a fpv pod or anything. Plus, it improves your aerodynamics a bit compared to a pod.

I only have a 15x15cm printer so parts had to be parted accordingly. After glueing thetwo canopys together you can remove the strut in the middle.

The hinges were mounted with M3 nylon screws and nylon nuts. Just add aa drop of glue on the thread. The canopy stays locked with magnets.

It´s no thing of beauty, but it works ;)

title: Compact 3 fans head for Dagoma DiscoEasy & DiscoVery 200 Printers

description.text:
2018-02-10 - Merci à Chikungunya pour ses vidéos :

2017-12-20 : Nouvelles Versions V3 (voir images)

  • Main_body_v3_Igus.stl : corps principal adapté pour 3 paliers IGUS RJ4JP-01-08 (ou 3 autres paliers à billes) , avec fentes pour compenser les jeux d'impressions, faciliter le montage, et bridage par vis + écrous (4x écrous M3 + 2x vis M3x10 + 2x vis M3x16)

  • Center_Key_v3_Reinforced.stl : clef de centrage renforcée pour une meilleure immobilisation de la tête (2x vis M3x16)

Cet ensemble, inspiré par la tête d’une « Ultimaker 2+ », est dédié aux Dagoma DiscoVery & DiscoEasy. Ses objectifs sont :

  • Un ventilateur pour le corps de chauffe alimenté en continue en 12 volt – monté avec l’adaptateur préconisé par E3D pour ces éléments chauffants.
  • Deux ventilateurs de refroidissement symétriques alimentés en parallèle en 12 volt sur le circuit dédié.
  • Corps compacts en X et Y (voir image dédiée pour l’adaptation des dimensions dans les slicers)
  • Implantation d’un roulement long du côté de la courroie pour réduire le jeu de translation.
  • Bridage de la tête recommandé par E3D.
  • Bridage symétrique des courroies (pas de différence de hauteur : tension constante) ; les bouts des courroies sont rabattues sous la pièce « Center Key »
  • Hauteur améliorée (notamment par rapport à la « Easy ») pour pouvoir imprimer plusieurs objets à la suite (limité par le passage des courroies à 46 mm)
  • Suppression des 6 minutes d’attentes en fin d’impression dans le End Code.
  • Possibilité d’évoluer vers un direct drive en adaptant la pièce « Center Key ».

BOM :

  • 8 x vis M3x8
  • 9 x vis M3x16
  • 1 x Palier long LM8LUU (pour V1 & V2)
  • 1 x Palier court LM8UU (pour V1 & V2) ,
    sinon pour V3, 3 x paliers courts IGUS RJ4JP-01-08 ou 3 x paliers courts LM8UU
  • 3 x VENTILOS 30x30x10 Dc 12 volt
    avec raccord rapide : https://e3d-online.com/30x30x10mm-dc-fan
    ou sans https://e3d-online.com/30x30x10mm-dc-fan-with-long-cable
  • 1x CONDUIT de VENTILO : https://e3d-online.com/v6-injection-moulded-fan-duct

Edit du 2017-08-20 : nouvelles versions renforcées du corps principal et de la clef de centrage : Main_Body_v2.stl & Center_key_v2.stl (voir image n°10)

Edit du 2017-08-22 : deux nouveaux supports plateaux "FLAT" sont disponibles sur le lien suivant pour les DiscoVery et DiscoEasy qui utilisent cette tête afin de gagner quelques millimètres perdus en Z: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1854220. Ces plateaux sont conçus pour fonctionner avec la " Boucle d'effort courroie GT2" pour le chariot Y : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1853611

Edit du 2017-09-30 : un TUTO pour ADAPTER le MARLIN (MKS / DiscoEasy) 
a été réalisé par Eowindel et est disponible dans l'onglet "Comments" 
Edit du 2017-10-09 : un firmware, adapté pour cette tête 
avec les dernières améliorations du Marlin 1.1.6,
a été réalisé par JJJpnt et est disponible au lien ci-dessous :

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2577212

Edit 2017-11-05 : des chariots Z(x) adaptés à cette tête (avec des tiges X  démontables rapidement, avec le fin de course X déporté, et avec 2 options de montage pour des vis trapézoïdales) sont disponibles ci-dessous:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2627287
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2627391
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2668020 <-- Merci de bien lire en détail ce remix

Edit 2018-02-18 : un guide câbles a été conçu par iCedric:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2798072

This set is dedicated to Dagoma DiscoVery & DiscoEasy printers and inspired by « Ultimaker 2+ » head. Its objectives are :

  • A dedicated fan for the heating body continuously supplied in 12 volt - assembled with the offical fan adapter recommended by E3D for their heating elements.
  • Two symmetrical cooling fans, supplied in parallel in 12 volt on the dedicated circuit.
  • Compact body in X and Y (see dedicated image for size adaptation in slicers)
  • Implementation of a long bearing on the side of the belt to reduce the translational clearance.
  • Head assembly design recommended by E3D.
  • Symmetrical clamping of the belts (no difference in height: constant tension); The ends of the belts are folded under the "Center Key"
  • Improved height (especially for the "DiscoEasy") to be able to print higher objects one after the other (limited by the belt to 46 mm)
  • Possibility to cancel the 6 minutes of waiting of the End Code.
  • Possibility of evolving towards a direct drive by adapting the design of the «Center Key».

EDIT 2017-08-20 : new stronger versions of Main_Body_v2.stl & Center_key_v2.stl (see picture n°10)

BOM :

  • M3x8 – qty 8
  • M3x16 – qty 9
  • LM8LUU bearing or equivalent– Qty 1
  • LM8UU bearing or equivalent – Qty1
  • FANS 30x30x10 Dc 12 volt – Qty 3 https://e3d-online.com/30x30x10mm-dc-fan or https://e3d-online.com/30x30x10mm-dc-fan-with-long-cable
  • FAN DUCT : https://e3d-online.com/v6-injection-moulded-fan-duct

YouTube :
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3luorJZO3m0
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uhIYDECE2Ko

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2 Extended

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

as fine as you can 60, 100, 150 um

Infill:

33%

Notes:

Print with PolyMax (Polymaker) Filaments, & 3D Lac spray onto glass support.

Please take care - for the main_body part to avoid all support in the area where the belt is clamped into a slot

Veillez à ne surtout pas mettre de support dans la fente de bridage de la courroie de la pièce centrale.
Fusion 360

Assemblage

La vidéo présente comment chacune des pièces s'emboite, néanmoins elle ne montre pas les passages de câbles, ni le serrage des courroies qui sont des étapes critiques.

  • Les câbles doivent être passés dans le trou central avant de mettre le roulement long. Il faut ensuite refermé la fente avec la petite rondelle et une vis M3x16.
  • Le passage et la fixation des courroies (voir image n°14) doivent être faits avant de fixer la pièce supérieure "Center Key" qui vient alors replier et écraser le retour des courroies et brider la position de la tête E3Dv6.

Performances (layers 100um, nozzle 0.4 mm, 3D Benchy model at 50% of its size)

Si la courroie ne passe pas et que tu as besoin de poncer, cela signifie que ton slicer a dû mettre des supports dans cette région alors qu'il ne faut surtout pas metttre de support dans cette zone. Il y a une image dédiée au principe de montage des brins de courroie. Après chaque passage de brin de courroie, on peut utiliser un tournevis fin ou une clef allen fine pour pousser à fond les brins de la courroie dans les encoches. La petite rondelles et la longue vis doivent précédemment avoir été mis en place ( pour refermer et rigidifier la fente) sinon la pièce sera écartelée.
Je crains que dans ton cas tu doives ré-imprimer une nouvelle pièce en veillant bien à ne pas mettre de supports dans la fente de passage de courroie....

comments.text: Les "roulements" (plus exactement les "paliers") ont par définition un jeu fonctionnel pour pouvoir glisser. Néanmoins ce jeu provoque la possibilité de faire onduler l’extrémité de la tête. Le fait de mettre un palier long (ou de deux paliers courts) permet d'obtenir une meilleure stabilité angulaire et donc une meilleure précision d'impression. De plus le fait d'avoir deux ventilos de refroidissement symétriques impose de venir placer le troisième ventilo pour le radiateur dans le sens de la largeur. Cette tête est effectivement alors plus large que les versions Dagoma, mais plus précise en terme de stabilité d'impression et plus efficace au niveau de l'homogénéité thermique.

Effectivement ces clips (en non picots) sont assez fins, et en fonction du type de filament utilisé (je préconise le PolyMax de PolyMaker) peuvent être plus ou moins fragiles, et donc casser plus ou moins facilement ... lorsqu'on insert les paliers...
Néanmoins, c'est étonnant qu'ils cassent lorsqu'on retire les supports qui sont - à priori - positionnés sur la face opposée. (Les fichiers STL sont pré-positionnés pour être imprimés sans avoir à changer l'orientation). Ton filament n'est peut-être pas adapté à ce type de sollicitations?
Certaines personnes m'ont expliquées qu'ils cassaient ces clips volontairement lorsqu'ils inséraient des paliers IGUS. Si le montage des paliers est naturellement serrés, ces clips ne sont alors d'aucune utilité. Plusieurs pièces de Dagoma (comme les chariots XZ) ne possèdent pas de "clips" anti-retours.
Donc, libre à toi de faire un essais de montage de paliers en cassant ces clips et en perçant la coque pour adapter des vis. Ton idée est intéressante. N'hésites pas à partager ici ton remix si tu souhaites faire ce type de modifications.

Bonjour Guillaumef78
Tu as trois solutions, les deux premières étant d'adapter le StartGcode (c'est ce que j'ai fait et ce que je préconise).
1) Tu peux faire des changements de repères XY (G92 X Y http://reprap.org/wiki/G-code/fr#G92:_D.C3.A9finir_la_Position ) pour recentrer le palpeur avant son palpage en plusieurs points, puis faire de même pour la buse.
2) Tu peux également remplacer le G29 Z (palpage multipoints) par un G28 Z au centre du plateau.
3) Si tu souhaites modifier le firmware, je t'invites à aller sur la page Facebook DagomaNiack car des liens vers des firmwares adaptés y sont mentionnés. N'étant pas compétent en la matière, je ne partage pas de Firmware modifié ici et n'ai pas eu besoin d'en faire.

remixed_from.title: E3D V6 40mm Fan Snap on with Zip tie tabs

description.text:
My E3D clone fan was just to loud and I had the feeling that I got heat creep, so I wanted to get a bigger (40mm) and therefore quiter fan.

I liked the snapon design of this (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:354723) and this (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2058949) but it was just to bulky and didn't quite fit with the hotend and carriage.
I also liked this (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:506958) design with the angled fan, but the snap on didn't fit for me.

So I kind of took both ideas and combined them in one design.

WIP ideas:
The only issue I have is, that the air blows through the E3D just fine, but has no propper path to escape, so it might flow down to the printing area. If anybody has suggestions, put it in the comments and I might try it.

author: djeff3d

title: Metal Detector Assembly with 10"/5" Coaxial Coil
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a DIY Project for a Metal Detector. The diameter of the coils are 254mm (10") and 127mm (5"). When the coil is inserted you can use silicone to fix it and create protection against environmental effects (water,..). There is a hole for a coax connecting wire (i.e. RG58, RG59,..) on each coil gap.

You will need to print the four parts of the coil (A to D) and four pieces of the swallowtail block. The coil parts will be connected with the swallowtails. The holes in the swallowtail are to apply silicone or glue for the final assembly. To connect a stick you have to print the CoilHolder and the AnkleJoint.

You can design your own AnkleJoint if you use another type of stick.

The AncleJoint is connected with a 40mm long M6 nylon screw. There are also parts for a quick release clamp.

The stick is an electrical installation tube with an outer diameter of 25mm. To create a telescope there are two pieces (Endpiece and Slider) available. The larger tube is also an installation tube but with an outer diameter of 32mm.

Further parts for the battery holder and handheld will follow when testing is completed.

Update 20 Aug 2017: New Version of Coil_D Part with channel for bucking coil cables.
Update 27 Aug 2017: Added more photos of the first design, Simple and Pro Handgrip.
Update 11 Sep 2017: The parts for the battery pack can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2529149
Update 26 Oct 2017: Added the clip which is needed to fix the telescoping part. Plus a photo of that specific detail.

Assembly

Print the four coil parts (A to D) and four swallowtail connectors. The four coil elements will be conected with the swallowtails. You can apply some silicone or glue through the holes in the swallowtail pieces. There hare two holes and a channel for connecting coils and feeder cables on coil part D. If everything (coils, feeder cables,..) have been installed and tested you can also apply silicone into the coil gaps to protect the coils and connections against environmental effects.

Next you add the coil holder. There are also holes for applying silicone (as for permanent fixation).
Now the AncleJoint is insertet into the coil holder. It must be fixed with a 40mm long M6 nylon screw, don't use any metal screws - which could have negative effects on the function of the coil. There are also parts for a (optional) quick release clamp.

A swallowtail block will connect two coil elements. Later this will be the lower side of the coil. Coil Design

For the beginning you can start with only one coil for transmitting and receiving:
Single Coil: 26 turns of 0,5mm enamel copper wire, inner diameter of the coil: 254mm

The more advanced version uses three coils:
Outer Coil:
26 turns of 0,5mm enamel copper wire, inner diameter of the coil: 254mm for transmitting

Inner Coils:
41 turns of 0,4mm enamel copper wire, inner diameter of the coil: 127mm for receiving
6 turns of 0,5mm enamel copper wire, placed on the receiving coil as bucking coil, must be connected serial to the transmitting coil but with reversed winding.

For winding the coil it is good to prepare a nail-form on a plain sheet of plywood. Make sure the board is big and thick enough to keep the nails at their place. Use a tool do get a perfect round shape. We used an old PCB piece with two notches for the nails.
Make sure you cut off the nailheads (use a grinder) and deburr the sharp edges. You can also add some duct tape to cover the nails before winding the coils.

It is good to have a tool for forming... Create a form for the coils... Wind the turn on the form and use waxed string to fix the coil before removing. TX Coil already wrapped with waxed string and plastic ribbon. The shielding aluminium tape is still missing. Inner coil for RX and 6 turns for loopback (bucking coil). You can see the waxed string which fixes and forms the coil.

comments.text: How is the telescoping part of the bar fixed? Would not it have been necessary to install the clamp in addition?
comments.author: kosta_art

comments.text: I just uploaded the missing part (Clip) which test was ongoing but seems to be strong enough. There's a photo of the spcific detail as well. Drill the two holes into the rod where the clip will be placed. Make sure their positions match the endpiece. Put the endpiece on the lower (sliding part) and the slider of the upper end (fix it with some silicone). Slide everything in the upper rod and fix the endpiece with some silicone. Select your favourite length and drill the missing holes in the inner rod. Fix everything with the clip.

This is a low cost, low power bar robot project. There are many here on Thingiverse already but these require air compressors, mains voltages and have Bill of Materials that run into the hundreds of £'s or $'s.

This design has most of it's parts 3D printed. Is designed to run from a USB battery pack and some AA batteries. (Keeps the power levels safe which is important when working with liquids and allows you to take the machine to parties, the garden or beaches with relative ease).

If you make your own one I would love to see it. :)

description.text:
This is an expansion kit for my SpaceX Falcon 9 Model found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2457148

****Model Update: A new .stl file has been added that includes the beams that connect the boosters to the Falcon Heavy core stage. Print two of the "booster-core connector" files and use them as the top booster connections. Print two of the "booster connectors" for the bottom connections.

****Many of you asked, so here it is, the Strongback is now available here! https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2779030

This kit allows you to build a Falcon Heavy as well as attach a Crew Dragon capsule (Dragon V2) to your model.

Instructions:

  1. Print a complete Falcon 9 model from the link above as well as two additional first stages (pieces 1-4, landing legs, and grid fins.

  2. Print 4 of the booster connectors and insert them into the 4 large holes in one of the Falcon 9 first stages. Connect the two addition first stages using the corresponding holes.

  3. Print 2 booster nose cones and connect these to the top of the two boosters. These use the same rotate-to-lock connectors as the interstage on the original model.

  4. Print the Crew Dragon capsule, trunk, and nose cone. Either the Dragon or the cargo fairings from the original model can be attached to the top of the core stage.

description.text:
C'est unanime, le support bobine BQ n'est pas bien pratique à l'usage.
J'ai donc pris l'initiative de créer un nouveau support mais à rouleaux.
Il suffit donc de poser la bobine sur les rouleaux, peu importe la taille il n'y a rien à régler.

Rien de bien compliqué.
Il vous faut 4 roulements à épaulement 10x5x5 et 2 tiges filetées de 5mm * 123mm
On imprime le tout à 200µ et 15% avec du PLA BQ
On rode les pas de vis des supports avec une vis de 5.
Les pièces de maintien des axes sont à ébavurer soigneusement afin de ne par trop coincer au montage.

Remarques :
Si votre fil se coince, la bobine risque de tomber sur le plateau
Reste à imaginer une sécurité pour palier à ce problème. En attendant, nous vendons les verres de rechange
Le support dépasse un peu sur l'avant de l'imprimante ce qui gène un peu le guide câbles quand la tête est très haute. En fait je pouvais reculer la bobine mais en augmentant le porte à faux ou en diminuant les flasques des rouleaux. Ce compromis ne devrait pas poser trop de problème même pour une pièce de 180mm de haut

Vous en lirez plus sur le forum Premium http://premium-forum.fr/viewtopic.php?f=52&t=1608

It is unanimous, the BQ spool is not very practical to use.
So I took the initiative to create a new support but with rollers.
So just put the spool on the rollers, no matter what size there is nothing to adjust.

Nothing very complicated.
You need 4 shoulder bearings 10x5x5 and 2 threaded rods 5mm x 123mm
The whole is printed at 200 μ and 15% with PLA BQ
Screw the threads of the supports with a screw of 5.
The axis holding parts must be carefully deburred so that they do not become jammed during assembly.

Notes:
If your wire gets stuck, the coil may fall onto the tray
It remains to imagine a security to overcome this problem. In the meantime, we sell replacement glass
The support slightly exceeds the front of the printer, which slightly disturbs the cable guide when the head is very high. In fact I could back the reel but by increasing the cantilever or decreasing the flanges of the rollers. This compromise should not pose too much problem even for a piece of 180mm high

description.text:
Wanted to make it for a while, but wanted an easier conversion, which can be quickly remover back and forth.

It's purposely designed for Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus
All you need to do is swap cooler with pen holder

Enjoy :)

I tried to make this instruction as simple as possible. If you have any questions/comments - feel free to post in comments section, I'll try to answer them all.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

50%

Notes:

I printed it with ABS, but PLA should work well also.

Additional materials

I tried to keep it to minimum
You'll need
6 screws for holder part
2 screws from cooler
8 tiny rubber bands

Dimensions note

Pen tip is around 65mm away from extruder nozzle on Y axis

So your printing/drawing surface will be 200x135mm

For now it's good enough for me, but if you want to increase the printing surface a bit, you can try to mount it facing extruder, using a very short pen/marker

Z axis in my setup goes in negatives, with the one on photo pen tip is at -26.8mm on Z axis.
Its not a problem even for "home all axis" command, cause pen tip will go outside the bed and you shouldn't crash it into anything.

Just keep the pen tip form 0 to -30mm on Z axis

Compensation for Z axis is explained in slicer settings section

Step 1

Print the holder

Step 2

Put it together with screws and rubber bands

pens/pencils/markers with diameters up to 12mm should fit

Step 3

Remove the cooling fan, install holder

Step 4 (Preparing the picture to draw)

If you already have an SVG image, you can skip this step

I'm using Inkscape SVG conversion method.
It's explained a lot in similar projects so I'll keep it short :)

  • Set the document size to 200x165mm
  • Open the photo you want to use
  • Scale it to fit our "printing area"
  • Use Path->Trace Bitmap to convert it to black and white
  • Play with Trace Bitmap settings to get best quality picture
  • Delete the original photo
  • Save the black and white version as SVG
Step 5 (SVG to STL)

Common OPENSCAD method is ok, but I found an a bit easier way

  • Go to svg2stl.com
    It's still in "beta", but works pretty good most of the times
  • Upload your SVG
  • Convert it to STL, for Z extrusion you can use 1mm height, we'll adjust it in slicer
  • Download your STL
Step 6 (Prepare slicer)

I'm using simplify3d, you can find the "good to go" settings for Wanhao i3 Plus in files section

If you're using different slicer it should be easy enough to adjust it to use with yours

  • Measure the Z distance between extruder nozzle tip and pen tip. Easiest way is just "home all axis", extruder should go to bed level and you can measure the distance from bed to pen tip. Remember this value, let's call it "Zdiff"

  • Import your STL to slicer

  • Change model scale on Z axis to be 1mm more than your measured "Zdiff"

  • In your process settings go to advanced (for simplify 3d) and set "start at" value for your "Zdiff" - 0.2mm, you can play with this coefficient to make line thicker or thinner. "Stop at" value set as your "start at" + 0.2mm. So at layer height on 0.2mm you'll have exactly 1 layer

  • Make sure your "end script" don't move on X or Y axis after completion, but just goes up on Z axis (to avoid any drawn lines after your print is finished)

  • Prepare your Gcode. You should see something like one layer picture levitating over the printing bed.

  • Save it and enjoy your plotter mode :)

I'm more or less happy with a holder itself, it's good enough for me for now. Possibly I'll change it a bit and add more versions with different diameters of pen hole.

As I'm still playing with different slicer settings to make drawn picture look best, I'll update the settings section here, when I find the perfect ones.

Text version of Simplify3D settings

Simplify 3D profile for Wanhao in "Wanhao_Plotter.fff"

  • Extruder Tab - > Ooze control -> retraction vertical lift 2mm

  • Layer -> Layer height 0.2mm
    -> Top solid layers 1
    -> Outline shells 1

  • Temperature -> 20 bed/ 20 extruder, uncheck "wait for temperature to stabilize"

  • Advanced ->Layer Modification (as per your measurement)
    -> Ooze control -> uncheck "only retract when crossing open space"

title: Helo model Rocket & Launch Pad (Estes Style)

description.text:
This Item is still a work in progress. Need to figure out how to add hinges to make the rocket lets flip out. Help requested!  
How many times did you lose that model rocket you spent hours on as a kid? Stuck in a tree or on top of your neighbor's roof  that was alway my luck. What if I told you that you can rekindle that childhood spark with your 3D printed model rocket? Don't worry about all of your hard work going to waste , just print yourself another and go!

NEWS: 4-25-2010 Transformation Video from Rocket (takeoff) to Helicopter (recovery) http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ykivOqE-E18 4-23-2010 Assembly Video added on youtube http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jzO67dKLD4M

What you need to get flying: 3D Printed Parts: 3 X Helo Rocket Model Bottom 3 X Helo Rocket Model Top 4 X Rocket Launch Pad Arm 4 X Rocket Launch Pad Base Household Items: 1 X Clothes Hanger 4 X M6 Nuts (Optional) 3~6 X Rubber bands Aluminium Foil Miscellaneous Wires 9 Volt Battery 1 X Estes "A series motor" Tools: Makerbot Cupcake Cutters Super Glue 400 grit Sandpaper Building your own Helo Rocket

  • Print all 6 parts. Multiple parts will fit on each print.

  • Remove parts and lightly sand down the parts to make them workable, or leave them "Textured Makerbot Style" for added cool points :-)

  • Glue each Rocket top to bottom. There is a built-in lip for added strength and durability

  • Bend active hinge on the rocket top. All printers will produce a slightly different hinge. So play with your hinge and determine how much force its takes to bend it. (Warning: Do not repeatedly bend the active hinge back and forth it could break.)

  • Cut two small notches 1/3 of the way down the new assembly. This is where the rubber bands will attach later. Repeat for other two assemblies
    • 6) Glue all three nose cones together 7) Sand down the rocket to make it more aerodynamic, or leave it "Textured Makerbot Style" 8) Glue rubberband to allactive hinge so that it bends. (More pictures coming soon) 9) Test Fit rocket to make sure it fits snuggly in the bottom pocket Testing Rocket: A) Pull test 1) Install rocket motor into the rocket. 2) Hold the top of the nose come and pull the rocket out. 3A) If the fins flare out your set for test two . 3B) If Not, Check the rubber band tention. Tighten the rubber band. Go back to step 1 3C) If the Rocket motor is hard to pull out, Smooth down the inside of the fins. Go back to step 1 Building your own estes style rocket Launch pad 1) Print: 4 X Rocket Launch Pad Arm 4 X Rocket Launch Pad Base 2) Acquire 1 X Clothes Hanger 4 X M6 Nuts (Optional) A roll of Aluminium Foil 3)

Thinking about printing multiples and leaving them around Manhattan as a conceptual 3D graffiti art piece. Of course, filament is pricey and my bot is temperamental so that might have to wait for the time being.   
Enjoy!
The file is very small but can be scaled up easily to fit any printer build volume. Included both .thing and .stl files.

spices organizer

I was always amazed about RC hobby, robots, and the spider robots in particular. Surfing on the web, I found many variants, from the super sophisticated-fancy ones, with sensors all over, to the basic ones which looks smart, but aesthetically are not quite nice, with shaky legs and simple geometric shapes.
So, I decided to design one, that looks decently designed, but with a simple core: 3 degrees of freedom per each leg, driven by the cheap but noble TowerPro SG90 servo, and the by the moment. all controlled by an Arduino UNO. I remark by the moment, because during the next period, I will become fancy too, and will add more sensors and connectivity, so I will go for another board. Allso, the way the legs were designed, allows to print more and make a 6 leg robot, or more. Today I only have an Arduino UNO, that limit the I/Os.
This is my first project with 3D printing and Arduino, so there is a lot of learning, and nerdy stuff. I publicly apologize my girlfriend for the noise of the printing hours in the apartment. There will be more, but I promise that in between I will print something nice for you.
I was planning to make this post after it was finished, or at least complete the first version, but instead, I thought it was a good Idea to share it as it is now, to get some feedback from users and get recommendations, ideas and critics.

During the comming weeks I will upload more parts and instructions about how I did it.

On this video a little test I've done because anxiety is a problem when 3D printing is a long way of waiting.

title: Alienware 13 R3 Riser Feet V2
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is the second version of my riser feet for the Alienware 13 R3. This version is much more robust than the first version. These clip onto the outside of the ventilation ports at the rear of the machine, providing a much stronger anchor than V1 - which only used the rear rubber 'foot' on the underside of the machine to secure to.

Again I have originally designed them to use a rubberised material for the clip and foot of the riser, while the body is which ever plastic you want to use. There is a version included that can be printed using a single material though, but I would strongly recommend using the rubber version. I found the single material to be a little too tight on the vent and was worried it could break it. Using a flexible material for the contact points still gives an excellent connection but it gives way as it is clipped on thus reducing the risk of breaking the laptop's casing.

There is also the Alienware logo on the riser as well, because, why not :D

Printed using black PLA and green FlexPLA from Rigid.ink - other filament re-sellers are available! ;)

-UPDATE-
Based on feed back (thanks WanaGo :D) I have uploaded an experimental version that has a cutout that I hope will act a bit like a hinge to allow single extruder users to use the clip without risk of breaking. PLEASE USE AT OWN RISK (sorry just covering my rear end ;)

title: Ultibots Kossel V-slot magball roller carriage with tension adjust

description.text:
Note 12/22/2017: Updated D version has some minor reinforcements and some other small refinements. Created it after a failure on a PLA printed carriage of mine. Probably wouldn't of had any problems if I had used ABS or PETG, but hey, figured it was worth some modification.

This is a tension-adjustable V-Slot magball carriage (42mm spacing) derived from the Ultibots experimental carriage for the D300VS by Brad Norman found here.

Remix is to allow for an expanded range of tensioning, a reinforcement on the top edge of the bottom belt clamp to make initial tension adjustment by "rolling" belt with needle nose pliers easier, and the hardware flexibility to use 2x m3 bolts of lengths between 25 and 50mm. Also, holes pass completely through the model to make support removal simple.

The screw "clamping" the carriage to the extrusion should be tightened so that the carriage rolls easily over a couple seconds when released (before belt attachment, obviously). Carriage should not "free fall", nor should it sit in place, when released.

When attaching the belts, I secure the "top" end of the belt with the wedge, and then pull the other end of the belt through the bottom clamp hole with a pair of needle nose pliers. I then twist the pliers, rolling up the excess belt, until I'm sure it's very close to the needed tension, and then I shove the bottom wedge into the clamp hole. I find that final tension adjustment of the belt is best done using Michael Hackney's method of employing the Easy Tension app to tune the belts so they vibrate at 39-41hz when "plucked".

I'm removing the "in progress" tag, as this version is working well for me, and while I might make a change later I have no plans to.

Printer:

D300VS

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

20% Triangles

Notes:

The version I am using was printed in PETG, but ABS or Nylon should all work great as well. PLA may be a little on the stiff side for tightening, but should work. 20% infill with 3 .4mm perimeters seems fine, but of course, those are just guidelines.

Supports are required, but I don't use a raft. Using a raft shouldn't cause any issues though.

This is a robust spool holder using only two standard 608zz bearings as the metal parts, everything else can be 3D printed on printers with at least 120x120x120 build area.
I designed it for my Kodama Trinus to sit on the top of the enclosure. The rounded edge fits perfectly against the edge of the enclosure, providing steady alignment. I also created a feeder part that fits into the spool holder hole on the enclosure panel. Initially meant to be on the side, I moved that panel to the top to directly feed the filament to the extruder head without major bends. It works great for my setup, hope you can get some use out of it for yourself!

Printer:

Kodama Trinus

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.15 - 0.20

Infill:

30%

Stand

You'll have to print two of the stand halves and glue them together. I used cyanoacrylate and had to sand the joints down a bit for a snug fit.

description.text:
I was tiring of the plastic HS1177 camera mounting holes stripping. Yes i can buy replacement cases, or metal case, but the 1177 camera itself doesn't differ from version to version so instead i got rid of threaded plastic in favor of a backplate which contains nut captures on either side for a 3mm bolt that we all have laying around.

For a finishing touch i used a exacto knife to cleanly cut off the protruded (old) mounting holes flush with the rest of the camera.

NOTE: This does move the pivot point of the camera back (or camera forward if you think about it) by roughly 8mm so plan accordingly, but i have not seen any issues with this thus far.

title: The Triptych - Puzzle Box
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The Triptych is a puzzle box designed by Daniel Brown (That's me!). It has three different mechanisms that each require a different method to open, figure out all three and the lid will slide right off.

The finished box is 70mm x 70mm x 100mm.

You will need to print 9 total parts, files are oriented in the intended position but feel free to tweak as required, scaling will alter tolerances and is not recommended. The box and lid will take the longest to print.

1 x Box.
1 x Lid.
1 x Plug.
6 x Pins. (These can be substituted for 5mm x 5mm brass pins if you have the time to cut and polish them, classy though!).

Follow my amazing guide image for easy assembly. The solution will be available in a later section!

THIS IS A BETA RELEASE, I HAVE NOT PRINTED THIS YET.

Feel free to edit, print, share, and gift this file and any prints of the box as much as you like. Please give credit wherever possible and link back to this post. Do not sell this file or any prints of the box for any reason, if you wish to make money with it please contact me for permission first.

Contains small parts, not suitable for children.

Thank you and enjoy :)

WARNING!

11/8/17 - Beta release - The box works in a simulated environment and has tolerances built in with 3D Printing in mind. This will be updated as soon as I have printed a box myself.

Clean up or sanding may be required for smooth operation, make sure all parts slide and move freely before fully assembling with pins as you may permanently lock the box!

See below for assembly instructions :)

The Triptych was designed in Fusion 360 over a few months and iterations. Future modifications and variants may be available as time goes on.

I've always had an interest in puzzles and the like, it only seemed sensible to have a go at making my own.

SPOILER ALERT

I don't recommend you read this if you want to enjoy solving the puzzle box, take heed!

No, really.

HINT: The three methods for unlocking are gravitational, centrifugal and pneumatic.

The top pins open by being in a vertical position, they fall into the body releasing the lid. Depending how tight your pins are they may need a tap to fall all the way.
The side pins open by centrifugal force, you spin the box and they slide across into the box releasing the lid.
The plug is seated in the box and opens using pneumatic force, blow into the rear hole and the plug will push up into the lid, push against the lid to slide it open (providing you have dealt with the first two mechanisms).

Balance all three to successfully slide open the lid, if you did this without cheating, well done! ;)

PART OF FULL PROTON PACK BUILD - NEUTRON THROWER ALSO AVAILABLE

Thrower: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2442928

This is the Pack part from my 3D printed Ghostbusters Proton Pack build.

The prop was made using various measurements from the gbfans.com wiki. Changes were made to have it 3D print easily, and space was made inside for all the electronics.

Inside the Neutron Thrower is an arduino, which powers the lights. There is a sound board for the SFX, which is toggled be a small set of relays, this then powers the speakers in the back of the pack.

The output of the sound in the video on the Neutron Thrower page shows what sounds the pack can make. In the finished prop all of the wiring went down the hose and connected to power and speakers in the Proton Pack itself.

With this item I have included a parts list which should help you out, it's honestly not that hard to assemble. Most the parts should print flat on the bed in one orientation or another only the Cyclotron parts will need support material. Everything else can be orientated to be printed without.

The prop is designed with holes for LEDs which sat behind opaque plastic in the Cyclotron. Lighting in the powercell came direct from blue LEDs which I have also created a mount for.

To finish the look you will need at least some wires, hose and the iconic rainbow ribbon cable. I also added machine bolts to hold parts in place and give it an industrial look.

Size wise, this was reduced by 10% as I'm a slim chap and thought the full size would look out of place. I also reduced the depth of some parts that didn't need to be so bulky to recreate the look.

description.header: Video of Thrower for SFX example
description.text:
<iframe allowfullscreen="None" frameborder="0" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/QdX_AjVV2cY" ></iframe>
Footage of lights and sound in the thrower, sound actually comes out the pack speakers

Assembling the prints

It was printed in parts and glued together using tabs inserted into slots. The glue I used was two part epoxy resin. Once all the elements of each part was fixed together I laid them out on a piece of MDF and traced around the finished loosely arranged parts.

Knowing I was going to add lights to and electronics to the build I cut semi-circular holes in the backplate to allow access to the cavity. To actually fix the parts to the backplate I used wood glue to attach blocks to the inside of the backplate, then screwed with black screws the parts into place.

Straps from an ex-army backpack were bolted to the backplate in suitable places. One piece of advice I'd give is to put more padding where your shoulder blades touch the solid back. After a day of wearing this, the points of my shoulder blades were bruised where they'd been against the solid wood all day.

The 'centrecover' parts didn't need any glue as it was just held in be the friction of its adjacent parts.

I painted the parts with normal spray paint primer, then a couple of coats of black spray paint mostly, and aluminium colour spray paint on those parts. Then I added the stickers, which I referenced images and recreated myself in Adobe Illustrator as I could create them just the right size that way.

The finishing touched included wires or plastic ducting between the parts, the recognizable rainbow ribbon cable and a few machine screws.

After the last cosmetic parts were added it had that 'factory finish' look, which I them proceeded to ruin by weathering the whole thing. Light strokes of silver acrylic paint to create the scratches, then brown and black painted on and rubbed off all over to give it the greasy dirty used look. It's a fun step and brings the project to life.

Pictures with captions below.

All seperate parts assembled - paper template behind is full size. Prop is 10% smaller. Painted parts on wood which was used for back plate Parts ready to be fixed to pack plate Finished pack, 'factory finish' paint job (without weathering) Final painted prop

Standing with another Ghostbuster for a photo Posing with other people Back with another Ghostbuster Neutron Wand lit up (it flashes) Shot from behind Side view - shows I slimlined the design to make it lighter and more con friendly

Booster parts. Boosterframe1_1 sits on top of this assembled part. Screw or glue in place once assembled. Fix directly to your pack plate. Parts 1 - 4 are the only part that should require proper support material, no flat surfaces to lay down on the bed. Small amount of support required for part 1_2 Whatever method you use to mount your thrower, can be affixed to this. Also created a bracket to glue HGA onto adjacent part. I swapped out ion1_4 for a more flexible Nylon rod. These are split in 1/2 so can be printed flat on the bed. LED mount (not pictured) for this part fits inside the box and can hold our 5mm LEDs. All parts have a flat surface, orient that on your print bed, no support required. Full parts list.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Inspired by https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:64847 and Expanding on my Mini Rack Mount system (inspired by: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1936196) i decided if you are gonna put a Raspberry pi, and some arduinos in a rack then what is more vital than a plethora of SD cards and USB drives? TADA!!! the corner of the design says floppy Disks , i was trying to make a funny, but my big nozzle messed it up it just looks like an imperfection. it is funny though from floppies to SD they really are kind of the exact same thing... Funny how that works...

-T

P.S. Stay tuned I'm about to unveil a whopper... and not the kind from BK either. But speaking of BK (Burger King) if you find my designs useful tips come in handy to feed my cheesburger addiction...lol

A NOTE ON SCALE:

different slicers different scales i can tell it best like this the dimensions of the face plate are 180mm wide 50mm tall 2mm deep, the demensions of the tray itself are 164mm wide 50mm tall and 17.061mm deep. that is the best way to scale it in different slicers, in cura they work out the box, i only use slic3r and Cura. i wont be using cura much long after they release machine control in the prusa version of slic3r.

when i design things in blender 1 CM is 1MM so if i had to guess at a general scale they are 10x bigger than the real thing but i always have to scale them up .. to be honest this is the one thing i havent really gotten around to figuring out. in the beginning i just compared the dimensions, and then i figured out blender would scale them to be the right size for cura and stopped messing with it.. if its not broke dont fix it mentality ... :)

title: Mega Anti-Tangle Spool Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
It's time for a useful spool holder. I got my first roll of PETG about a week ago, and the first thing I realized is how frustrating it is to keep the filament on the spool, so I just had to come up with a solution for it.

Meet my Mega Anti-Tangle Spool Holder. Designed for total ease of use and compatibility with many sizes of spools, this spool holder uses the weight of the spool to clamp around it at 4 points, making it almost impossible for a rogue coil to spring off and cause you issues.

This has been designed and tested to work with spools in the range of 145mm to 210mm in diameter, and anywhere up to 94mm in width. It can probably work with spools greater than 210mm (dia), but I have not been able to test it further. It can even be folded away quite compact, which was a totally accidental perk.

Also designed to be 3D printer friendly, none of the parts require supports, just print as already oriented in the stl files.

The only additional components you will need are 8x 608 bearings, however there is 2 different versions of the arms available, and I strongly recommend using the ones with "w-m3" in the title, which allows for reinforcing the bearing holders with M3 screws and nuts. This therefore requires an additional 8x M3x15 screws and 8x M3 nuts, but if you want to risk it without the screws you can just use the arms with "blind" in the title.

Quantities you need to print:

1x "sh base p1 v1"
2x "sh base p2 v1"
2x "sh base p3-left v1"
2x "sh base p3-right v1"
2x "sh arm left blind v1" OR "sh arm left w-m3 v1"
2x "sh arm right blind v1" OR "sh arm right w-m3 v1"
2x "sh arm cross beam top v1"
2x "sh arm cross beam bottom v1"
4x "sh roller male v1"
4x "sh roller female v1"

Quick and dirty assembly video: https://youtu.be/kYG6KbLXhzM
Quick and dirty demonstration: https://youtu.be/sLDd7RN0kj4

Hope you all like this and find it useful!

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

comments.text:
Can you describe how the M3 bolts are used?
Obviously they go into the holes and connect to the nuts in the hex holes, but how does that hold the bearing in, or the arm to the base, or whatever it is intended to do? I can see them in the video, but it's not at all evident what they contribute to holding things together...and after assembling my PLA version it's fairly apparent that they do need to be held together. I get the feeling you may have neglected to mention a component or method.
comments.author: BETLOG

comments.text: They don't hold anything together, it's simply to reinforce the studs for the bearings, because they take the entire weight of the spool and you are relying on 8mm circle layer strength, which isn't a lot. Nothing should need to be held together any further, the base and the supporting cross beam (that says DESIGNED BY GW) do a pretty good job holding the rollers in place, for me and a few others I have talked to anyway. I have used the this spool holder for about a month now with no problems. Just make sure the cross beams are in place properly, the arms have slight notches that lock them in place.
comments.author: BETLOG

comments.text: Ah, ok. I might look into printing a washer/disk to secure them somehow. Maybe it's because I used PLA, but mines pretty much falling apart, despite being quite tight in some joints, others are barely gripping each other at all. Y-Belt Tensioner for Anet A6 with mounting-holes for fixation on a ground plate.

Makes use of

  • two standard Anet M3x18 bolts
  • two M6x60 bolts and nuts for tensioning mechanism
  • optional four M6 bolts for ground plate-fixation
  • washers for each of the bolts are recommended

The two parts of the carriage may be glued, but that might not be necessary.
The tension of the belt should be build up by pulling the carriage by hand, then fix it into position by retighten the two M6 screws.
No drilling on the original Anet-parts is required. The big orange part and the white ones on the photos should embrace the Anet-front plate, which is only visible on the rendered image. The end covers for the Y-poles will not be needed any more.

author: lazydude241

title: Raspberry pi case screw hole mount for security camera with pi-camera

description.text:
I created this to use various Raspberry PI commercial casings as camera mount with the include pi-camera (no-IR filter) as security camera setup. This one fits nicely on a camera screw and tighten with a M10 bolt.

Great to combine with the RPI v3, which has in-build WIFI. So only power needed and you're good to go!

The setup that I used:

  • Raspbian Jessie lite (terminal only)
  • RPI 3 board
  • Camera (IR filter or the no-IR filter version)
  • Enable the camera connector with "sudo raspi-config" (first option under menu 'interfaces')
  • To make sure the /dev/video0 device is present the right driver needs to be loaded to be able to use it with 'motion', make sure to add 'snd-bcm2835' as line in the file /etc/modules and reboot.
  • Install 'motion' with "sudo apt-get install motion"
  • Then edit the file '/etc/motion/motion.conf', to set a lot of things: "sudo nano /etc/motion/motion.conf"
    width 1024
    height 768
    framerate 25
    webcam_maxrate 10
    webcam_localhost off
    ffmpeg_output_movies off
    stream_localhost off
    target_dir <set it to a more convenient folder; for example /captures; make sure to create it also and use "chmod 755 /captures">
    locate_motion_mode preview
    locate_motion_style redbox
    event_gap 2
    output_pictures center
    quality 80
    text_changes on

There are more setting to play with but with this basic setup you should have a work motion camera detection system storing images with each event.

  • test with "sudo motion -n -c /etc/motion/motion.conf" to run it directly. Then open a browser on your network to :8081 to check the stream

  • make motion start permanently on boot: "sudo nano /etc/default/motion" and add make 'start_demon on'

Now your need to reboot to see it in action

If you want automatic emails with every motion detection based on the configuration above, then use the next steps as well:

Install mail tools:
"sudo apt-get install ssmtp"
"sudo apt-get install mailutils"
"sudo apt-get install mpack"

Edit ssmtp config to define your smtp settings of your ISP/email provider:
"sudo nano /etc/ssmtp/ssmtp.conf"

Stuff to set:
root=postmaster
mailhub=[smtp address]:[port nr]
hostname=[your RPI host name]
AuthUser=[your user id or email]
AuthPass=[your smtp password]
FromLineOverride=YES
UseSTARTTLS=YES

(assuming you will use TLS or SSL; check google search for details to use GMAIL settings or none-secure smtp use)
Then you can test sending an email with an attachment from your motion capture folder (as set by 'target_dir' in the motion config)

mpack -s "My test email" /captures/.jpg

Now to add the 'automatic email feature' to motion edit the motion config file: "sudo nano /etc/motion/motion.conf"
And set the option 'on_picture_save' to execute the mpack command from above. It should look like this:
on_picture_save mpack -s "Dude!! I've detect motion on your camera!" %f

One last hint: make sure to clean your captures folder occansionally (e.g. with a cronjob script) to remove older files, else your SD-card might fill up after some time.

To do that: edit the file /etc/cron.daily with "sudo nano /etc/cron.daily"

Add the following line to kill older jpg files from the folder:
find /captures -name '*.jpg' -mtime +7 -exec rm -f {} \;

Reboot, and that should be the basics to get it running!

description.text:
23-09-2017 Update! Added gcode file that Heat the nozzle to 210C and bed to 50C for more accurate leveling. I recommend to unload the filament before start the leveling so no filament will flow and interfere with the leveling.

This is a Ender-2 Bed leveling procedure. It start with 3 point bed leveling. It is done 2 times. After that, the Ender print a small square on the bed, This takes 4 minutes. You must load PLA before the test. The square should stick to the bed.
Se video for detailed instruction. Happy leveling
https://youtu.be/DI-yhPi53mQ

Printer:

Ender 2

Notes:

Square is included in the Code

description.text:
I needed an indicator holder that would be more consistent. I designed this to fit over the body of the extruder stepper motor and clamp on using a small screw and nut that I had laying around. The side is designed to have a 1/4-20 nut placed inside then mount a Harbor Freight Pittsburgh 1" travel indicator using a 3/4" bolt.

This set up does not allow you to measure the entire print bed but it did get close enough that I was able to make the necessary adjustments to level my bed better.

If this helps you please consider leaving the designer a TIP!

comments.text: After getting frustrated myself with everything I saw and tried on here that I thought would work for my MK2, I could not find anything that was sturdy and would not move. I did not post this until I put it to the test myself and was successful in holding the indicator with consistency. Also it is measuring where the actual extruder is instead of the rods. When it is on the rods as soon as you slide it back and forth it loses its accuracy. This design is solid as it holds everything very tight. I would not have posted it if it didn't. What are you finding that is wrong with it? Maybe with your constructive input I can get a design out there that might do what you need. And yes, a TIP is always nice to give when someone provides something that helps you.

description.text:
I wanted a case to store the various bits I had laying in a drawer. The case should hold a lot, allow for various height bits, and be small and lightweight. I wanted it to lock to prevent inadvertent opening during transport.

This design allows for adjustable bit holder height and quantity by allowing multiple bit holder "bars" to be added/removed. The bit "bars" rotate allowing for easy access to the bits and the ability to store bits that are taller than the case is thick.

The only issue is trying to get the bit bar in the bottom hole as it is a tight fit. Some filing of the bar may be required to allow it to snap in place.

Printer Brand:

MakerGear

Printer:

MakerGear M2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Support needed only for the Lock piece and for the locking section on both the top and bottom pieces.

The bit "bar" is difficult to print. I was successfully able to print it standing up to keep the circles on the end well formed.

I wouldn't go less than 20% infill, but more certainly wouldn't hurt. 20% worked well for me.
For the hinges, I had planned on using a 1/8 inch bar/dowel, but a 1.5 inch long #6 screw worked really well.
I used Fusion 360. A link to the project file can be found here: http://a360.co/2fyZvyr

title: Tronxy x1 extruder cover replacement with radial fan mount

description.text:
I was having some issues with the hotend on my x1 having a hard time getting up to its target temperature. the extruder fan is placed a little higher in this design so its pointing more at the heatsink than at the hotend. this seemed to solve most of the issues I was having. because the radial fan mount is on the left side it takes a little bit of off the print volume which is why I have also included a more compact x-axis endstop.

I have created a new version of the cover that places all the fans a bit smarter around the hotend. I have also included versions of both the cover and the endstop mount that include easy connectors for these cable chains: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11978. I have also added two compatible fan ducts that are slight modifications of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1954001 and https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2088006. note: these fan ducts are untested, I am using a version of the spaceship fan ducts on my own printer but lost the file and had to recreate it.

comments.text:
It's a pity, the cover doesn't fit anet a8 radial fan and its half-round circular duct: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1954001
The cover's fan mount is too high so the duct collides with the cover bottom corner and the holes for the fan are too small, drilling them would probably break them as there's not much plastic around them.
stock cover was working with this holder: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2330842
comments.author: goga

comments.text: I have updated the cover and included two options for fan ducts, I personally use an altered version of this spaceship fan duct: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2088006. but I have also included a version of your semi-circular fan duct (I have not tested it yet though so I might've screwed up some measurements).

title: Remixed BLTouch Fan Mount for Anycubic Kossel Plus Linear

description.text:
This is a remix of Disjaukifa's "BLTouch Fan Mount for Anycubic Kossel Plus Linear"

I really liked the idea of this mount for the bltouch. It seems to get the probe in the tightest to the effector. I did, however, think it could use a little weight loss program and I wanted to be able to mount it with the circuit board hidden. I completely remodeled it in Fusion360 with all of the critical geometry reproduced, while shaving volume and adding fillets for strength. It is still plenty stiff for mounting the already lightweight probe.

I printed this with 3 shell layers and 50% infill. Still dialing in my printer, so the print quality in the photos isn't what it could be. Also, I didn't put enough thought into cable management; maybe next iteration.

Refer to the original thing for firmware setup.

Thanks!

description.text:
Used this (In german it´s a "Klappenstütze") as a spare part for my campervan. "stuetze2" probalbly needs support - every other part doesn´t. Use at least ABS with 100% infill to make it durable.

You can buy the original spare part for only a few bucks - so printing isn´t really worth it.
But drawing it in FreeCad and printing it good enough, that the parts snip together, was an very interessting challange to me.

I am not very optimistic that it will last very long - but I will give it a try :)

Note: I would "ping" around the large plastic nut with a medium size hammer before trying to remove the nut. Tapping around the nut will help knock loose the nut and make it much easier to break loose!!!!!!! Also, I would place one of these on the tank nut and use small hammer to bump it around tapping on the head of the printed tool. Doing this should make on and off of the plastic tank nut easy on and off. Don't bust nut or tool or you hit too hard...... :)

These are tools for removing the large plastic fuel pump ring-nuts for replacing automotive fuel pumps. These should fit most of them that have the extruding teeth around the outer edges for gripping with.

There are 3 types:

The "Wedge_OFF_TOOL" and the "Wedge_ON_TOOL" tools are single purpose for either taking the nut on or off. You may be able to turn one of them over or upside down and reverse the direction with a bit of patients on some applications. Others may need both. With the Wedge Tool, you will use a large screw driver or other strong steel tool to wedge in between the two risers on the side to wedge the nut around.

The "Pliers_ON-OFF_Tool" can be flipped over and used to remove the nut as well as re installing the nut. I would use vise-grip pliers an clamp them on at the end of the tool. Should work well.

The "ScrewDriver_ON_OFF_TOOL" will need a 1/4" diameter steel rod of sort to slide down the hole in the middle of it to give you leverage to install on or remove off the nut. The hole is 5/16" diameter and may can use a 1/4" socket drive extension as well. Anything steel that will slide down in the hole to give leverage will work.

Between all of them one should do the trick. Study the photos an your application and i'm sure one or other will do the job.

Print these strong using maybe minimum of 50% fill or more. The stronger the better. Should last and become your go too tool when working on fuel pumps that use the large round toothed nut as pictured.

Thanks, Rick.

title: Mr. Dressup - Casey and Finnegan's Treehouse
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Up here in Canada, during the 80's, there was a great children's show called "Mr. Dressup". The show featured puppets named Casey and Finnegan. One of the main sets was a treehouse in a large trunk, where they would perform together during sketches.

So I decided to take the nostalgia train and design the tree house. I haven't designed the tree to go along with it yet, but will be doing that next as an add on.

Ive included all the files I designed on Tinkercad and also included a whole treehouse file where you can just print the whole thing. With the way the windows and door are, it may be best to print each piece seperate.

All files are easy enough to scale up or down depending on what you desire. The model is scaled to the exact dimensions of the original full size one, just smaller. Enjoy!

** I havent added the shingles yet or the siding but am working on that part shortly. Cheers!

I couldn't find any decent looking bike light on the market so i made one.

It runs on 3x 1w cree leds connected in series, voltage is regulated with step down converter, that allows you to connect any kind of battery.
I glued LEDs to body with epoxy glue, seems to do the job.

I added photo with lights on, on photo you can see gap between leds, thats the way camera captured it. In reality it looks like one solid block of light.

print_settings.Notes:: When I printed, it took 4 hours with settings listed above. However post-printing I found that some of the letters on the inscription were partially missing pieces of them due to error (which I attribute to the resolution), so if you want more precise lettering I would suggest scaling up the model. The model is actually quite small right now, so if you want a decent sized trophy I would definitely suggest scaling up before print.

description.text: Just a fun trophy for my extended family's fantasy football league (dubbed "Cuzlife"). I wanted to make a cheap trophy that looked good, so I created this. I will spraypaint this after print, for I want a nicer, finished look. Feel free to remix 'Cuzlife' text to change to the name of league or anything else. Thank you to 'videogamefreak1' for design of football (on tinkercad), otherwise creation is all mine.

Printer:

Qidi X-One

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

10%

Notes:

When I printed, it took 4 hours with settings listed above. However post-printing I found that some of the letters on the inscription were partially missing pieces of them due to error (which I attribute to the resolution), so if you want more precise lettering I would suggest scaling up the model. The model is actually quite small right now, so if you want a decent sized trophy I would definitely suggest scaling up before print.
I will finish using plastic primer and sandpaper to first give model a smooth look, and then use painters tape to spraypaint specific regions with shiny gold and black Tamiyah plastic spraypaint.
This is my first venture into tinkercad! I did this in about 1 hr. 30 min.

description.text: The truncated octahedron is space filling. Blocks made from combinations of this polyhedron nest nicely together and form interesting structures. Five blocks are included here; the simplest is the basic truncated octahedron. Two blocks consist of pairs of polyhedra; one pair joined by square faces, the second by hexagonal faces. The fourth block is made of three truncated octahedra joined by hexagonal faces and the fifth block contains four polyhedra joined by square faces. OpenSCAD code is included.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator (5th Generation)

Rafts:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Notes:

trunc_o_hexagonal_three.stl may need support

The coordinates used to define the vertices of the truncated octahedron have an origin at the center of the polyhedron. The truncated octahedron has six square faces and eight hexagonal faces. The principal axes, x,y, and z, pass through the centers of the opposing square faces. To form the fifth block from 4 copies of the polyhedron, leave one copy at the origin, move a second copy along the x axis by the distance between square faces, a third copy along the y axis by the distance between square faces, and the final copy along both x and y by the distance between square faces. Block 5, a square shape, is formed.

This process can be repeated to get an infinite array of polyhedra joined by square faces; the faces passed through by the z axis remain uncovered. To fill space duplicate this large planar array and translate it along each of the 3 axes by half the distance between square faces. The packing can be demonstrated by using multiple copies of block 5, trunc_o_square_four.stl.

Introducing my version of the Nerf Rapidstrike / Stryfe Flywheel cage! I've been working on this one for a while now and I'm very happy with the results so far.
This flywheel cage will drop straight into the Nerf Rapidstrike and Stryfe with no mods required to the shell.
The cage is a friction fit for most 130/180 motors with a small amount of post print work required depending on your printer setup.
There are both straight and canted variants available, the canted version works better in the Stryfe or a Rapid Pistol conversion due to the shorter barrel length.
Features a dart guide (Different for the Stryfe and RS) for zero-jam dart feeds and a barrel alignment guide that fits straight into the Nerf barrel.
This is the "Standard" 43.5mm cage so not a high crush variant, will likely have another variant of this up soon.
Feedback, comments or critiques are always appreciated!

author: hubschrauber

title: AC Power box for Hypercube with SSR

description.text:
I'm building my own version of Tech2C's Hypercube with various changes. For example, I am using silicon heater that is using 220V AC power. Also, my bottom horizontal rails are a bit higher than in original design.
So, in order to get silicon heater working, I'm using SSR. And of course I wanted to isolate high voltage connections as much as possible and came up with this solution that combines cover for power button, power chord connector, a fuse and high voltage part of SSR.

Autodesk Fusion 360 link to the project: http://a360.co/2uOMp1S

The screws and nuts are:
2x M3x35 screws
7x M5x10 screws
2x M3 nuts
7x T-slot nuts for 2020 extrusion profile (look for original hypercube page)
I also used 2 washers for M3 screws just in case.
